{"source_key":"sha256-166a6f077fd8acca604befa465c21cd9","record_index":100,"record_hash":"sha256:9cd569ed3f9ab83d3d61485b36a396cabfb65eab978bab3120b90aab1c537dc0","timestamp":"2026-05-21T19:41:39.777Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"My take: **don’t make the review feature another `but agentlog` command.** Keep `but-agentlog` as the evidence layer; build the review-adjacent thing above it as a projection/browser.\n\nCurrent state I caught up on:\n\n- Handoff is basically settled as `skim` + bounded `show`.\n- The docs explicitly leave review sharing out of `but-agentlog`: [handoff-design.md](</Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md>) and [Including-turns.md](</Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md>) both say the review layer should come later.\n- Real branch data is already messy: 50 related sessions, 173 turns. That confirms the review view needs ranking/highlighting, not “dump transcript for PR.”\n\nThe review-adjacent product should answer:\n\n> “What useful agent context helps me review this change?”\n\nNot:\n\n> “Here is every chat message the author had.”\n\nI’d design it as a **review evidence bundle**:\n\n1. Start from a PR/review/branch/change.\n2. Use `but-agentlog` to find related sessions and turns.\n3. Score or highlight likely relevant turns using:\n   - direct review/change/branch observations\n   - nearby capture time\n   - changed paths, later\n   - tool activity/tests\n   - user prompts that mention intent, risks, edge cases\n4. Render a compact timeline:\n   - prompts\n   - assistant claims\n   - tests run\n   - files/tools touched\n   - unresolved questions\n   - “not enough evidence” gaps\n5. Let reviewer drill into redacted exact records only when needed.\n\nBoundary I’d keep hard: **`but-agentlog` should not own review copy, PR payloads, web DTOs, publishing, or “this session authored this PR” claims.** It should expose facts like “turn observed branch X / review Y / change Z.” The review layer can interpret those facts.\n\nOne thing I’d add to the mental model: this is closer to **review provenance** than transcript sharing. The best UI is not a chat viewer first. It’s a reviewer aid: “what was the agent asked to do, what did it claim, what did it test, what might it have missed?”","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-21T19:41:39.777Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}